[!TIP] Hypersensitivity Vs Autoimmune disease
Hypersensitivity is an abnormal immune response to a harmless stimulus. When the 'stimulus' is a self antigen, we call it autoimmunity.

Autoimmune diseases can be classified in the same way as hypersensitivity conditions. but IgE is not involved in autoimmunity.
so in the bale below, there is no "type I" in the autoimmune categories

Autoimmune diseases caused by antigens against cell surface receptors: [[moreAutoimmuneDiseases.png]]

Cutaneous manifestation of tuberculosis

  • Lupus vulgaris - post primary infection; presents on head and neck. Heals with scarring.
  • Tuberculosis veruca cutis : warty lesion; occurs with skin innoculation in an invidual who is partially immune.
  • Scrofuloderma: discharge of an infected lymph node onto the skin. Heals with scarring.
  • Tuberculides - hypersensitivity reactions to underlying TB infection.
    • These lesions do not contains bacilli, show evidence of granulomatous inflammation and resolve with successful TB treatment.
    • commonest [[Dermatology#Q 7 Erythema nodosum|erythema Nodosum]];
    • Similar lesion on the calves is called erythema induratum of bazin <- this one ulcerates.
